## Content
````
The provided source code from the file `docs\specs\001-foundry-sdk-alignment.md` outlines a specification for aligning the Agent Framework and Foundry SDK, which are two software development kits designed to cater to different audiences and scenarios. The primary objective of this document is to clarify the positioning of both SDKs for developers and customers, highlighting their distinct functionalities and providing guidelines on their usage. Foundry SDK serves as a thin-client SDK for accessing agent services and is built from REST APIs in multiple languages. Meanwhile, the Agent Framework SDK provides a general-purpose framework for developing agentic applications and supports the orchestration of heterogeneous agent systems across local and cloud environments.

The specification defines goals and success metrics to ensure seamless integration and minimize user friction when using both SDKs concurrently. These goals include enabling developers to harness the full capabilities of the Foundry SDK and facilitating the creation of multi-agent orchestrations. Success metrics focus on ensuring ease of use and reducing complexity compared to other agent frameworks. To address existing issues, such as disjointed developer experiences and customer confusion regarding when to use each SDK, the document proposes API changes.

Key components include helper methods to retrieve or create `AIAgent` instances using the `PersistentAgentsClient`. The method `GetAIAgentAsync` retrieves an existing server-side agent as a `ChatClientAgent`, while `CreateAIAgentAsync` creates a new server-side agent. These methods cater to different parameter requirements, such as agent IDs, model information, and configuration options, utilizing asynchronous tasks to manage operations. The focus on detailed parameterization, including options for tools, response formats, and metadata, supports robust agent configuration.

The document elaborates on end-to-end code samples to demonstrate practical applications of the SDKs. Various examples highlight the process of creating and managing agents with Foundry SDK while utilizing the Agent Framework SDK for execution and orchestration. The document emphasizes seamless integration, showcasing scenarios like creating agents with persistent state, running conversational interfaces, managing conversation threads, and orchestrating multiple agents. The orchestration example involves creating distinct agents with specific roles and using a `SequentialOrchestration` to process input and manage agent interactions.

To summarize dependencies, all helper methods rely on external types such as `PersistentAgentsClient`, `ChatClientAgent`, and `CancellationToken`. These dependencies are critical for interacting with the agent services and managing asynchronous operations efficiently. The integration with these external systems ensures that data flows smoothly through the SDKs, addressing potential bottlenecks and maximizing stability and scalability. By demonstrating clear and well-structured SDK utilization, the specification provides comprehensive guidance for developers to implement aligned and efficient agent systems.
````
